 critical questions that address pressing social issues. Drawing on the changing relationship between political parties and workers in nineteenth-century Chicago, de Leon concludes that if workers’ collective rights are to be preserved in a global economy, workers must chart a course of political independence and overcome long-standing racial and ethnic divisions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aLabor movementzIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy19th century. 0aLaborzIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy19th century. 0aOpen and closed shopzIllinoiszChicagoxHistoryy19th century. 0aWorking classxPolitical activityzIllinoiszChicagoxHistory. 4aLabor History. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / Midwest (IA, IL, IN, KS, MI, MN, MO, ND, NE, OH, SD, WI).2bisacsh  aCollective bargaining rights, unions, labor rights, worker rights, labor policies, organized labor, conflict in organizaed labor, politics and laborm global economy, political independence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145588940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801455889423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801455889/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles